04490nmm a2200613Ia 9780520922877DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20232000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209228777 a10.1525/97805209228772doi  a(DE-B1597)542829  a(OCoLC)1163878575  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aF869.S39bC597 1999eb 7aHIS0361402bisacsh04a979.4/61004951/009222211 aYung, Judy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnbound Voices :bA Documentary History of Chinese Women in San Francisco /cJudy Yung.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (558 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUnbound Voices brings together the voices of Chinese American women in a fascinating, intimate collection of documents—letters, essays, poems, autobiographies, speeches, testimonials, and oral histories—detailing half a century of their lives in America. Together, these sources provide a captivating mosaic of Chinese women's experiences in their own words, as they tell of making a home for themselves and their families in San Francisco from the Gold Rush years through World War II.The personal nature of these documents makes for compelling reading. We hear the voices of prostitutes and domestic slavegirls, immigrant wives of merchants, Christians and pagans, homemakers, and social activists alike. We read the stories of daughters who confronted cultural conflicts and racial discrimination; the myriad ways women coped with the Great Depression; and personal contributions to the causes of women's emancipation, Chinese nationalism, workers' rights, and World War II. The symphony of voices presented here lends immediacy and authenticity to our understanding of the Chinese American women's lives.This rich collection of women's stories also serves to demonstrate collective change over time as well as to highlight individual struggles for survival and advancement in both private and public spheres. An educational tool on researching and reclaiming women's history, Unbound Voices offers us a valuable lesson on how one group of women overcame the legacy of bound feet and bound lives in America. The selections are accompanied by photographs, with extensive introductions and annotation by Judy Yung, a noted authority on primary resources relating to the history of Chinese American women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aChinese American womenxBiographyxCaliforniaxSan Francisco. 0aChinese American womenxSourcesxHistoryxCaliforniaxSan Francisco. 0aChinese American womenxSourcesxSocial conditionsxCaliforniaxSan Francisco. 0aChinese American womenzCaliforniazSan FranciscovBiography. 0aChinese American womenzCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryvSources. 0aChinese American womenzCaliforniazSan FranciscoxSocial conditionsvSources. 0aChinese American womenzCaliforniazSan FranciscoxSourcesxHistory. 0aChinese American womenzCaliforniazSan FranciscoxSourcesxSocial conditions. 0aWomen immigrantsxSourcesxHistoryxCaliforniaxSan Francisco. 0aWomen immigrantszCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryvSources. 0aWomen immigrantszCaliforniazSan FranciscoxSourcesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520922877?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520922877423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520922877/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles